    {
      name: "Collaborative State",
      id: "rt-collab",
      icon: "👥",
      phase: "Real-time",
      color: "#a855f7",
      sizes: ["medium", "large", "hyper"],
      short: "Last-write-wins → OT → CRDT — the algorithms that make 'multiplayer' software possible",
      keyInsight: "When two users edit the same document simultaneously, their edits will conflict. User A types 'Hello' at position 5 while User B deletes characters 3–7. If you naively apply both operations, the result is garbage. The merge strategy determines whether collaborative editing feels magical (Google Docs) or frustrating (email attachments back and forth). Two dominant algorithms exist: Operational Transform (OT, used by Google Docs) requires a central server to order and transform operations — simpler for the server author, but the server is a single point of failure and a latency bottleneck. CRDTs (Conflict-free Replicated Data Types, used by Figma) use mathematical properties to merge operations in any order on any node and converge to the same result — no central server needed, works offline, but generates more metadata and is harder to implement.",
      mentalModel: "Imagine two people editing the same whiteboard from different rooms, connected by video. OT is like having a referee: each person describes their edit ('I drew a circle at position X'), the referee transforms conflicting edits ('Person A's circle at position 5 needs to shift to position 6 because Person B inserted text before it'), and both whiteboards converge. The referee (server) must see every edit and transform it — if the referee goes offline, editing stops. CRDT is like giving each person a special kind of whiteboard where any sequence of operations in any order always produces the same final result — like painting with additive colors where the order doesn't matter because the physics guarantees convergence. No referee needed, but the whiteboard is more complex (it tracks the 'identity' of each brushstroke so it can merge deterministically).",
      detail: {
        what: "Algorithms for merging concurrent edits to shared state (text documents, drawings, spreadsheets, presentations) without coordination and without conflicts. The core challenge: when User A inserts character 'X' at position 5 and User B simultaneously deletes character at position 4, the operations were created against the same initial state but the state has diverged. Applying A's operation on B's state (where position 5 is now position 4 because of the deletion) would insert 'X' in the wrong place. (1) Operational Transform (OT): transforms each operation against all concurrent operations before applying. The transform function adjusts positions: 'insert at 5 after a delete at 4 → insert at 4.' The server acts as a central sequencer: it assigns a total order to operations and transforms each one against all preceding concurrent operations. Used by Google Docs (the most battle-tested implementation), ShareDB, and Firepad. Strength: well-understood, proven at scale, compact wire format. Weakness: server-dependent (offline editing is limited), complex transform functions (N operation types require N² transform functions), hard to implement correctly (Google's OT paper is notoriously subtle). (2) CRDTs (Conflict-free Replicated Data Types): data structures designed so that all concurrent operations commute — applying them in any order yields the same result. Each edit is tagged with a globally unique, totally ordered ID (based on a logical clock). Insertions reference the item they're placed after by ID, not by position — so position shifts don't cause conflicts. Used by Figma, Notion (partially), Apple Notes, and many modern collaborative tools. Libraries: Yjs (most popular, JavaScript/TypeScript, supports text/JSON/arrays/maps, ~30KB bundle), Automerge (Rust core with JS bindings, more academic rigor, larger bundle). Strength: works offline and P2P (no central server required), simpler reasoning about correctness (if the CRDT is correct, merging is always correct). Weakness: metadata overhead (each character carries a unique ID, increasing document size by ~10–30%), garbage collection needed to bound growth.",
        why: "Without a merge algorithm, collaborative editing degenerates into 'last writer wins' — whoever saves last overwrites everyone else's changes. This is the experience of editing a shared Google Drive file with auto-sync off: save conflicts, lost work, frustration. Real-time collaboration that 'just works' is the difference between a single-player tool and a multiplayer platform. It's now table stakes for any document/design/code editing product. Figma's collaborative editing is their most cited competitive advantage over Sketch (single-player). Google Docs defeated Microsoft Word Online largely through superior real-time collaboration (Google had a 5-year head start with OT). Notion's block-based collaboration is what makes it a team tool rather than a personal wiki. The choice between OT and CRDT has real architectural consequences: OT requires a central server (simpler infrastructure, but server is SPOF and adds latency — server round-trip required before edit is visible to collaborators). CRDT works peer-to-peer (more complex data structure, but local edits are instant and merging happens in the background — better UX on slow connections).",
        numbers: "Metadata overhead: OT operations are compact (operation type + position + content, ~20–50 bytes each). CRDT per-character metadata: Yjs uses ~10–15 bytes per character (unique ID + parent reference + content). For a 10,000-character document, Yjs state is ~150KB vs ~40KB for plain text — 3.75× overhead. This is manageable for documents but can be significant for large datasets. Garbage collection: Yjs supports 'snapshots' that compact the history, reducing state size to ~1.2× plain text. Latency: OT with central server: edit → server → other clients = server RTT (10–50ms within region, 80–200ms cross-region). CRDT without server: edit → local apply (instant) → background sync to peers (whenever network allows). Concurrent editor limits: Google Docs (OT): ~100 concurrent editors per document. Figma (CRDT): ~100 concurrent editors per file. Limits are usually UI-driven (screen gets cluttered), not algorithmic."
      },
      tradeoffs: [{ axis: "OT vs CRDT", left: "OT: smaller wire format, server is source of truth (simpler reasoning), but requires always-on central server and adds latency to collaboration", right: "CRDT: works offline/P2P, instant local edits, but larger metadata (10–30% overhead) and more complex data structures", pos: 0.6 }],
      sizes_cfg: {
        medium: {
          range: "Single-region, server-authoritative collaboration — Yjs or ShareDB",
          rec: "For most collaborative features (document editing, whiteboard, shared to-do lists): use Yjs. It's the most popular CRDT library, battle-tested in hundreds of production applications, and has excellent ecosystem support. Setup: (1) Install: `npm install yjs y-websocket`. (2) Server: run the y-websocket server (`npx y-websocket`), which manages document rooms and syncs state between clients. (3) Client: create a Y.Doc, connect to the server, bind to your editor. Yjs has bindings for: ProseMirror/TipTap (rich text), Monaco (code editor), CodeMirror, Quill, and many more. A full collaborative text editor can be built in <100 lines of code. For OT (if you prefer server-authoritative): ShareDB (Node.js, backed by MongoDB — well-tested, used by Concord and others). The server maintains the canonical document state and transforms operations. Simpler to reason about correctness but requires the server to be available for editing. Technology comparison: Yjs (CRDT, most popular, lightest memory footprint among CRDT libs, excellent editor integrations — strength: works offline, P2P-capable, huge community; weakness: understanding the underlying CRDT model has a learning curve). Automerge (CRDT, more academic rigor, Rust core — strength: richer data model including counters and nested objects; weakness: larger bundle size ~200KB vs Yjs ~30KB, fewer editor integrations). Liveblocks (managed service — handles presence, storage, and conflict resolution — strength: zero infrastructure, great React hooks; weakness: vendor lock-in, $25–100/month+). ShareDB (OT — strength: server-authoritative, MongoDB-backed, simpler mental model; weakness: requires always-on server, more complex for offline support).",
          tools: ["Yjs", "Automerge", "ShareDB", "Liveblocks (managed)"]
        },
        large: {
          range: "Sharded document servers with presence and awareness",
          rec: "At scale, you need to handle thousands of simultaneous collaborative sessions, each in its own 'room.' Architecture: (1) Shard by document ID: each document's collaboration room runs on one server, determined by consistent hashing of document_id. This gives you locality (all edits for one document go to one server) and horizontal scaling (add more servers as document count grows). (2) Use Hocuspocus (the production-grade Yjs server — handles persistence, authentication, authorization, hooks for custom logic, Redis for multi-server awareness). Or scale y-websocket behind a load balancer with sticky sessions keyed on document_id. (3) Separate awareness from document state: 'awareness' data (cursor positions, selection ranges, user avatars, typing indicators) is ephemeral and high-frequency. Don't persist it — keep it in memory only, broadcast via the same WebSocket but on a separate channel. (4) Persistence: save the Yjs document state to your database periodically (every 5 seconds or on every edit, depending on durability requirements). Yjs documents are binary blobs (Y.encodeStateAsUpdate) — store as a BLOB in Postgres or in S3. On room open, load the blob and apply it to a fresh Y.Doc. (5) Scaling awareness to many viewers: if a document has 1000 viewers but only 5 editors, you don't need all 1000 on the same collaboration server. Serve read-only viewers from a CDN-cached version updated every few seconds; only active editors maintain WebSocket connections.",
          tools: ["Hocuspocus (production Yjs server)", "Yjs y-websocket", "Liveblocks", "custom OT server"]
        },
        hyper: {
          range: "Edge-based CRDT with local-first architecture",
          rec: "At global scale with sub-100ms collaboration latency everywhere, the traditional 'connect to a central server' model fails — cross-continent server round-trips add 80–200ms per edit, making collaboration feel sluggish. The solution: edge-local CRDT state. (1) Cloudflare Durable Objects: each document's collaboration state lives in a Durable Object at a single edge PoP (the PoP nearest to the document's most active editor). Clients connect to their nearest PoP and are routed to the DO. Edits from nearby users apply instantly; edits from distant users arrive via PoP-to-PoP relay (~30–80ms). (2) Local-first architecture: each client holds a full copy of the document (CRDT state) locally. Edits apply instantly to the local copy (0ms latency — the best possible UX). Syncing with the server/peers happens in the background. If the network goes down, the user keeps editing — changes merge when connectivity returns. Yjs supports this out of the box. (3) Multi-region CRDT replication: document state is replicated across regions. Each region accepts local edits and merges with other regions asynchronously. CRDTs guarantee convergence regardless of merge order, so this is mathematically safe. The UX: edits are always instant (applied locally first), and cross-region merges are invisible (they just appear as 'remote user made a change'). Technologies: Cloudflare Durable Objects ($0.15/million requests + $0.20/GB-month storage — stateful edge compute, ideal for per-document CRDT state). Liveblocks Enterprise (managed collaborative infrastructure with edge presence). Custom CRDT + edge storage (most flexible, most engineering effort — build Yjs sync on your own edge network).",
          tools: ["Cloudflare Durable Objects", "Liveblocks Enterprise", "custom CRDT + edge storage"]
        }
      },
      levelUp: [],
      pitfalls: [
        { name: "CRDT bloat over time", desc: "CRDTs are append-only by nature — every operation is recorded in the history. A document edited 10,000 times accumulates 10,000 operations in its state, even if the current content is only 1,000 characters. Without compaction, document state grows without bound. Solution: Yjs supports periodic 'snapshots' that compact the document state, discarding tombstones (records of deleted items) and merging the history into a single state. Run compaction when document state exceeds 10× the content size. Automerge has similar compaction support." },
        { name: "Awareness data leakage", desc: "Persisting cursor positions, selection ranges, and typing indicators to the database wastes storage and creates privacy issues (users might not expect their exact cursor position to be stored indefinitely). Keep awareness data in memory only — it's ephemeral by nature. When a user disconnects, their awareness data should disappear within seconds. Yjs's awareness protocol handles this correctly by default." },
        { name: "Conflict resolution surprising users", desc: "CRDTs resolve conflicts deterministically, but the resolution might not match user intent. Example: two users simultaneously change the same word — User A changes 'cat' to 'dog,' User B changes 'cat' to 'bird.' A character-level CRDT might produce 'dbird' or 'bogd' depending on character IDs. This is 'correct' by CRDT math but confusing to users. Mitigation: use higher-level conflict resolution (word-level or block-level operations), or highlight conflicting regions for manual resolution." }
      ],
      examples: [
        { name: "Figma multiplayer — custom CRDT in Rust", desc: "Figma built a custom CRDT specifically designed for vector graphics operations (move, resize, recolor, group/ungroup). Their CRDT is implemented in Rust (compiled to WebAssembly for the browser client and running natively on the server). It supports ~100 concurrent editors per file with sub-50ms operation latency. Key design choice: operations are at the object level (move rectangle X to position Y), not the byte level — this produces much more intuitive merge results than character-level CRDTs because graphic operations are naturally commutative (moving and recoloring the same rectangle in either order produces the same final state)." },
        { name: "Notion blocks — hybrid merge strategy", desc: "Notion uses a hybrid approach: block content (text within a block) uses OT-like conflict resolution with the server as sequencer. Block properties (color, type, toggle state) use CRDT-like last-writer-wins. Comments are append-only (no merge needed — all comments are preserved). Block ordering uses a fractional indexing scheme that allows insertion between blocks without reindexing. This hybrid approach lets Notion optimize each data type for its specific access pattern rather than forcing everything through a single merge algorithm." }
      ],
      related: [{ id: "req-consist", label: "Consistency Model" }],
      children: []
    }
